          'Yes — select "1s" in the mode buttons above. The 1-second test captures your absolute peak burst speed. Because it\'s so short, scores are typically higher than longer tests. It\'s great for measuring your raw maximum CPS without endurance fatigue affecting the result.'
        ],
        [
          'How does the spacebar click speed test work?',
          'Visit our dedicated Spacebar Speed Test page. Click the test area to activate it, then press the spacebar as fast as possible. Each spacebar press registers as a click. Your spacebar CPS is measured and displayed in real time. Most people find their spacebar speed is 10–20% lower than their mouse click speed.'
        ],
        [
          'What is jitter clicking — and how do I test it?',
          'Jitter clicking is a technique where you tense your forearm and wrist muscles to create rapid vibrations that register as mouse clicks, achieving 12–16 CPS. Visit our Jitter Click Test page for a dedicated test with separate score tracking. Warning: jitter clicking can cause repetitive strain injury if done excessively — always take breaks.'
        ],
        [
          'What is butterfly clicking?',
          'Butterfly clicking uses two fingers (index and middle) alternating on a single mouse button to achieve 15–25 CPS. It\'s less physically demanding than jitter clicking but is banned on some competitive servers. Our Butterfly Click Test page tracks butterfly scores separately from your main CPS scores.'
        ],
        [
          'What is drag clicking?',
          'Drag clicking is a technique where dragging your finger across the mouse button registers multiple clicks per motion — potentially reaching 25–40+ CPS. It requires a specific mouse with the right surface texture. Most major servers including Hypixel ban drag clicking. Visit our Drag Click Test page to measure your drag CPS.'
        ],
        [
          'What is the reaction time test?',
          'Our Reaction Time Test measures how long it takes you to respond to a visual stimulus — specifically, clicking when the screen turns green. Average human reaction time is 200–250ms. Elite gamers react in 150–200ms. Under 150ms is exceptional. We offer this as a separate page from the CPS test.'
        ],
        [
          'Does CPS matter in Minecraft?',
          'Yes — especially in classic 1.8 PvP (no attack cooldown). Higher CPS means more hits per second, which translates directly to more damage in duels. On modern servers like Hypixel, hit registration caps around 13 CPS, so accuracy and aim matter more than raw speed beyond that threshold.'
        ],
        [
          'Can I take the CPS test on mobile?',
          'Yes. FastClickTest is fully mobile responsive. Tap the test area as fast as you can — touch events are registered identically to mouse clicks. Mobile CPS scores tend to be slightly lower than desktop mouse scores due to screen response limits, but the test is accurate for touch-based measurement.'
        ],
        [
          'Are my click speed scores saved?',
          'Yes — your scores are saved locally in your browser\'s localStorage. Nothing is sent to any server. Your best CPS and score history are stored privately on your own device. Clearing your browser\'s site data will remove them.'
        ],
        [
          'How to test click speed accurately?',
          'Use the 5-second or 10-second mode for the most accurate CPS measurement — long enough to average out lucky bursts, short enough that fatigue doesn\'t distort results. Take 3–5 attempts and compare. Your true clicking speed is closer to your average across multiple tests than any single peak result.'
        ],
        [
          'What is the world record for clicks per second?',
          'Dylan Allred from Las Vegas, USA holds the verified world record: 1,051 clicks in 10 seconds — an average of 14.1 CPS. This was achieved using butterfly clicking technique with a specialized gaming mouse. Some unverified claims go higher, but Allred\'s record is the most widely accepted benchmark.'
        ],
      ].map(([q,a]) => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">
            <span>{q}</span>
            <span class="faq-icon">▾</span>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-a">{a}</div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

